    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-10-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-10-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="56"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d56">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.51/2943</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Secretary of State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-23">October 23,
                            1930</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>When the British Ambassador called on me today he asked me about Dr. Schacht’s
                    visit. I told the Ambassador he had brought no message from his Government on
                    the subject of Germany’s condition or desires, and that his conversations with
                    me on the two occasions which I had met him had been as innocuous as those of
                    the typical British matron.</p>
                <p>I told him, however, that I had reason to believe, from unofficial sources, that
                    Germany had lost a good deal of her credits since the election and was up
                    against a hard situation. He said that he had the same impression.</p>
                <p>We agreed that we had a hard winter before us with respect to the effect of the
                    economic depression on the world.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>H. L. S[<hi rend="smallcaps">timson</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
